#: ../../../glossary.rst:146
msgid "array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:148
msgid "Used synonymously in the NumPy docs with :term:`ndarray`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:150
msgid "array_like"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:152
msgid ""
"Any :doc:`scalar <reference/arrays.scalars>` or :term:`python:sequence` that "
"can be interpreted as an ndarray.  In addition to ndarrays and scalars this "
"category includes lists (possibly nested and with different element types) "
"and tuples. Any argument accepted by :doc:`numpy.array <reference/generated/"
"numpy.array>` is array_like. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:160
msgid ""
">>> a = np.array([[1, 2.0], [0, 0], (1+1j, 3.)])\n"
"\n"
">>> a\n"
"array([[1.+0.j, 2.+0.j],\n"
"       [0.+0.j, 0.+0.j],\n"
"       [1.+1.j, 3.+0.j]])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:167
msgid "array scalar"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:169
msgid ""
"An :doc:`array scalar <reference/arrays.scalars>` is an instance of the "
"types/classes float32, float64, etc.. For uniformity in handling operands, "
"NumPy treats a scalar as an array of zero dimension. In contrast, a 0-"
"dimensional array is an :doc:`ndarray <reference/arrays.ndarray>` instance "
"containing precisely one value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:174
msgid "axis"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:176
msgid ""
"Another term for an array dimension. Axes are numbered left to right; axis 0 "
"is the first element in the shape tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:179
msgid ""
"In a two-dimensional vector, the elements of axis 0 are rows and the "
"elements of axis 1 are columns."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:182
msgid ""
"In higher dimensions, the picture changes. NumPy prints higher-dimensional "
"vectors as replications of row-by-column building blocks, as in this three-"
"dimensional vector:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:193
msgid ""
"``a`` is depicted as a two-element array whose elements are 2x3 vectors. "
"From this point of view, rows and columns are the final two axes, "
"respectively, in any shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:197
msgid ""
"This rule helps you anticipate how a vector will be printed, and conversely "
"how to find the index of any of the printed elements. For instance, in the "
"example, the last two values of 8's index must be 0 and 2. Since 8 appears "
"in the second of the two 2x3's, the first index must be 1:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:206
msgid ""
"A convenient way to count dimensions in a printed vector is to count ``[`` "
"symbols after the open-parenthesis. This is useful in distinguishing, say, a "
"(1,2,3) shape from a (2,3) shape:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:224
msgid ".base"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:227
msgid ""
"If an array does not own its memory, then its :doc:`base <reference/"
"generated/numpy.ndarray.base>` attribute returns the object whose memory the "
"array is referencing. That object may be referencing the memory from still "
"another object, so the owning object may be ``a.base.base.base...``. Some "
"writers erroneously claim that testing ``base`` determines if arrays are :"
"term:`view`\\ s. For the correct way, see :func:`numpy.shares_memory`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:235
msgid "big-endian"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:237 ../../../glossary.rst:374
msgid "See `Endianness <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endianness>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:239
msgid "BLAS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:241
msgid ""
"`Basic Linear Algebra Subprograms <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Basic_Linear_Algebra_Subprograms>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:243
msgid "broadcast"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:245
msgid ""
"*broadcasting* is NumPy's ability to process ndarrays of different sizes as "
"if all were the same size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:248
msgid ""
"It permits an elegant do-what-I-mean behavior where, for instance, adding a "
"scalar to a vector adds the scalar value to every element."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:261
msgid ""
"Ordinarily, vector operands must all be the same size, because NumPy works "
"element by element -- for instance, ``c = a * b`` is ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:264
msgid ""
" c[0,0,0] = a[0,0,0] * b[0,0,0]\n"
" c[0,0,1] = a[0,0,1] * b[0,0,1]\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:268
msgid ""
"But in certain useful cases, NumPy can duplicate data along \"missing\" axes "
"or \"too-short\" dimensions so shapes will match. The duplication costs no "
"memory or time. For details, see :doc:`Broadcasting. <user/basics."
"broadcasting>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:273
msgid "C order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:275
msgid "Same as :term:`row-major`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:276
msgid "casting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:278
msgid ""
"The process of converting array data from one dtype to another. There exist "
"several casting modes, defined by the following casting rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:281
msgid ""
"``no``: The data types should not be cast at all. Any mismatch in data types "
"between the arrays will raise a `TypeError`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:284
msgid "``equiv``: Only byte-order changes are allowed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:285
msgid ""
"``safe``: Only casts that can preserve values are allowed. Upcasting (e.g., "
"from int to float) is allowed, but downcasting is not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:287
msgid ""
"``same_kind``: The 'same_kind' casting option allows safe casts and casts "
"within a kind, like float64 to float32."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:289
msgid "``unsafe``: any data conversions may be done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:290
msgid "column-major"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:292
msgid ""
"See `Row- and column-major order <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row-"
"_and_column-major_order>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:294
msgid "contiguous"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:297
msgid "An array is contiguous if:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:299
msgid "it occupies an unbroken block of memory, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:300
msgid ""
"array elements with higher indexes occupy higher addresses (that is, no :"
"term:`stride` is negative)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:303
msgid "There are two types of proper-contiguous NumPy arrays:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:305
msgid ""
"Fortran-contiguous arrays refer to data that is stored column-wise, i.e. the "
"indexing of data as stored in memory starts from the lowest dimension;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:308
msgid ""
"C-contiguous, or simply contiguous arrays, refer to data that is stored row-"
"wise, i.e. the indexing of data as stored in memory starts from the highest "
"dimension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:312
msgid "For one-dimensional arrays these notions coincide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:314
msgid ""
"For example, a 2x2 array ``A`` is Fortran-contiguous if its elements are "
"stored in memory in the following order::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:317
msgid "A[0,0] A[1,0] A[0,1] A[1,1]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:319
msgid "and C-contiguous if the order is as follows::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:321
msgid "A[0,0] A[0,1] A[1,0] A[1,1]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:323
msgid ""
"To test whether an array is C-contiguous, use the ``.flags.c_contiguous`` "
"attribute of NumPy arrays.  To test for Fortran contiguity, use the ``.flags."
"f_contiguous`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:327
msgid "copy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:329
msgid "See :term:`view`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:331
msgid "dimension"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:333
msgid "See :term:`axis`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:335
msgid "dtype"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:337
msgid ""
"The datatype describing the (identically typed) elements in an ndarray. It "
"can be changed to reinterpret the array contents. For details, see :doc:"
"`Data type objects (dtype). <reference/arrays.dtypes>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:341
msgid "fancy indexing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:343
msgid "Another term for :term:`advanced indexing`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:345
msgid "field"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:347
msgid ""
"In a :term:`structured data type`, each subtype is called a `field`. The "
"`field` has a name (a string), a type (any valid dtype), and an optional "
"`title`. See :ref:`arrays.dtypes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:351
msgid "Fortran order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:353
msgid "Same as :term:`column-major`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:355
msgid "flattened"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:357
msgid "See :term:`ravel`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:359
msgid "homogeneous"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:361
msgid ""
"All elements of a homogeneous array have the same type. ndarrays, in "
"contrast to Python lists, are homogeneous. The type can be complicated, as "
"in a :term:`structured array`, but all elements have that type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:365
msgid ""
"NumPy `object arrays <#term-object-array>`_, which contain references to "
"Python objects, fill the role of heterogeneous arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:368
msgid "itemsize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:370
msgid "The size of the dtype element in bytes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:372
msgid "little-endian"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:376
msgid "mask"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:378
msgid "A boolean array used to select only certain elements for an operation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:392
msgid "masked array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:394
msgid ""
"Bad or missing data can be cleanly ignored by putting it in a masked array, "
"which has an internal boolean array indicating invalid entries. Operations "
"with masked arrays ignore these entries. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:398
msgid ""
">>> a = np.ma.masked_array([np.nan, 2, np.nan], [True, False, True])\n"
">>> a\n"
"masked_array(data=[--, 2.0, --],\n"
"             mask=[ True, False,  True],\n"
"       fill_value=1e+20)\n"
"\n"
">>> a + [1, 2, 3]\n"
"masked_array(data=[--, 4.0, --],\n"
"             mask=[ True, False,  True],\n"
"       fill_value=1e+20)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:409
msgid "For details, see :doc:`Masked arrays. <reference/maskedarray>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:411
msgid "matrix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:413
msgid ""
"NumPy's two-dimensional :doc:`matrix class <reference/generated/numpy."
"matrix>` should no longer be used; use regular ndarrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:417
msgid "ndarray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:419
msgid ":doc:`NumPy's basic structure <reference/arrays>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:421
msgid "object array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:423
msgid ""
"An array whose dtype is ``object``; that is, it contains references to "
"Python objects. Indexing the array dereferences the Python objects, so "
"unlike other ndarrays, an object array has the ability to hold heterogeneous "
"objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:428
msgid "ravel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:430
msgid ""
":doc:`numpy.ravel \\ <reference/generated/numpy.ravel>` and :doc:`numpy."
"flatten \\ <reference/generated/numpy.ndarray.flatten>` both flatten an "
"ndarray. ``ravel`` will return a view if possible; ``flatten`` always "
"returns a copy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:437
msgid ""
"Flattening collapses a multidimensional array to a single dimension; details "
"of how this is done (for instance, whether ``a[n+1]`` should be the next row "
"or next column) are parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:441
msgid "record array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:443
msgid ""
"A :term:`structured array` with allowing access in an attribute style (``a."
"field``) in addition to ``a['field']``. For details, see :doc:`numpy."
"recarray. <reference/generated/numpy.recarray>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:447
msgid "row-major"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:449
msgid ""
"See `Row- and column-major order <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row-"
"_and_column-major_order>`_. NumPy creates arrays in row-major order by "
"default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:452
msgid "scalar"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:454
msgid "In NumPy, usually a synonym for :term:`array scalar`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:456
msgid "shape"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:458
msgid ""
"A tuple showing the length of each dimension of an ndarray. The length of "
"the tuple itself is the number of dimensions (:doc:`numpy.ndim <reference/"
"generated/numpy.ndarray.ndim>`). The product of the tuple elements is the "
"number of elements in the array. For details, see :doc:`numpy.ndarray.shape "
"<reference/generated/numpy.ndarray.shape>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:465
msgid "stride"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:467
msgid ""
"Physical memory is one-dimensional;  strides provide a mechanism to map a "
"given index to an address in memory. For an N-dimensional array, its "
"``strides`` attribute is an N-element tuple; advancing from index ``i`` to "
"index ``i+1`` on axis ``n`` means adding ``a.strides[n]`` bytes to the "
"address."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:473
msgid ""
"Strides are computed automatically from an array's dtype and shape, but can "
"be directly specified using :doc:`as_strided <reference/generated/numpy.lib."
"stride_tricks.as_strided>`. Bounds validation can be enabled with the "
"``check_bounds`` parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:478
msgid ""
"For details, see :doc:`numpy.ndarray.strides <reference/generated/numpy."
"ndarray.strides>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:481
msgid ""
"To see how striding underlies the power of NumPy views, see `The NumPy "
"array: a structure for efficient numerical computation. \\ <https://arxiv."
"org/pdf/1102.1523.pdf>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:485
msgid "structured array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:487
msgid "Array whose :term:`dtype` is a :term:`structured data type`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:489
msgid "structured data type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:491
msgid ""
"Users can create arbitrarily complex :term:`dtypes <dtype>` that can include "
"other arrays and dtypes. These composite dtypes are called :doc:`structured "
"data types. <user/basics.rec>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:495
msgid "subarray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:497
msgid "An array nested in a :term:`structured data type`, as ``b`` is here:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:504
msgid "subarray data type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:506
msgid "An element of a structured datatype that behaves like an ndarray."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:508
msgid "title"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:510
msgid "An alias for a field name in a structured datatype."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:512
msgid "type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:514
msgid ""
"In NumPy, usually a synonym for :term:`dtype`. For the more general Python "
"meaning, :term:`see here. <python:type>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:517
msgid "ufunc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:519
msgid ""
"NumPy's fast element-by-element computation (:term:`vectorization`) gives a "
"choice which function gets applied. The general term for the function is "
"``ufunc``, short for ``universal function``. NumPy routines have built-in "
"ufuncs, but users can also :doc:`write their own. <reference/ufuncs>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:525
msgid "vectorization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:527
msgid ""
"NumPy hands off array processing to C, where looping and computation are "
"much faster than in Python. To exploit this, programmers using NumPy "
"eliminate Python loops in favor of array-to-array operations. :term:"
"`vectorization` can refer both to the C offloading and to structuring NumPy "
"code to leverage it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:532
msgid "view"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:534
msgid ""
"Without touching underlying data, NumPy can make one array appear to change "
"its datatype and shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:537
msgid ""
"An array created this way is a `view`, and NumPy often exploits the "
"performance gain of using a view versus making a new array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:540
msgid ""
"A potential drawback is that writing to a view can alter the original as "
"well. If this is a problem, NumPy instead needs to create a physically "
"distinct array -- a `copy`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../glossary.rst:544
msgid ""
"Some NumPy routines always return views, some always return copies, some may "
"return one or the other, and for some the choice can be specified. "
"Responsibility for managing views and copies falls to the programmer. :func:"
"`numpy.shares_memory` will check whether ``b`` is a view of ``a``, but an "
"exact answer isn't always feasible, as the documentation page explains."
msgstr ""
